Implements a minimal, character-buffer text editor simulation used to model how a real code editor would react to a scripted sequence of keystrokes (auto-closing brackets/quotes, type-over, auto-indent, block expansion, dedent-on-backspace, and column-preserving up/down movement). It's the stateful engine that `interpret` (in the parent `editor` module) drives one key at a time; this file has no notion of "commands" or scripts, only single-character insertion and named-key dispatch via `apply_key`.

The `Behaviors` struct (defined in the parent module) is a bag of per-profile toggles — `auto_close`, `type_over`, `auto_indent`, `indent_unit` — captured once at `Sim::new` and consulted on every keystroke; changing that struct's fields requires updating every read site here (`type_char`, `enter`, `dedent_delete`, `apply_key`'s `Tab` arm). Character classification helpers (`auto_close_of`, `ends_with_opener`, `is_auto_close`, `is_quote`) live in the parent module and encode which characters pair/trigger indent continuation — this file only orchestrates their results, so adding a new bracket type means editing the parent module, not this one.

Key behavioral specifics an editor must know:
- `type_char` order of precedence: auto-close pairing first, then quote auto-pairing, then type-over (stepping past an existing matching close/quote char under cursor), then plain insertion. Type-over only fires for chars where `is_auto_close` or `is_quote` is true.
- `insert_pair` inserts both chars then decrements cursor by 1 to sit between them — this is the only way opens/closes get paired; `cursor -= 1` assumes exactly one char was just placed after the pair.
- `enter` special-cases `{|}` (cursor sitting between an already-typed open and close brace) into `block_expand`, which produces three lines (open line, indented blank body, dedented close line) and repositions the cursor on the body line — math is `cursor -= 1 + base.chars().count()`, sensitive to `base`'s exact length.
- `indent_newline` only adds one extra `indent_unit` when the current line (right-trimmed) ends with an "opener" per `ends_with_opener`; it does not track nested indent depth beyond the current line's leading whitespace.
- `dedent_delete` treats Backspace as deleting a full indent unit only when everything before the cursor on the line is pure spaces (not tabs) and `auto_indent` is on; otherwise it deletes exactly one character. The unit-rounding formula `len - (len - 1) / unit * unit` assumes `unit >= 1` (enforced via `.max(1)`).
- `up`/`down` preserve the visual column by measuring offset from `line_start`, clamped to the target line's actual end (`line_end`); `down` bails out (no-op) if there's no next line rather than moving to end-of-buffer.

All positions are character (not byte) offsets into `Vec<char>`, consistent with the doc comment's ASCII assumption — using byte-oriented string APIs elsewhere against `cursor`/`buffer` would misalign. No function here panics on out-of-range cursor movement; boundary checks (`saturating_sub`, `.min(...)`, buffer-length guards) are used throughout instead.